english:
  title: Royal Edict Declining the Resignation of Minister Kim Bu-sik from His Honors
  author: Choi Ham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have received and considered the memorial you have submitted regarding your request to decline the honors of Meritorious Subject of Loyalty, Stabilization, and National Peace, Inspector of the Grand Commandant, Guardian of the Gate, Attendant to the Sovereign, Magistrate of the Ministry of Personnel, Overseer of National History, Premier Duke, and Concurrent Tutor to the Crown Prince.

    Truly, to bestow rank upon the virtuous and reward the meritorious, to honor the worthy and encourage the good—these are the very foundations by which a nation is governed. This is the sacred duty of a sovereign.

    When there is one possessed of pure loyalty and unflinching righteousness, who harbors the wisdom to govern and reform, such a person harmonizes heaven and earth when placed in high office, and cleanses corruption when commanding armies. For such service, though you were to reward him with treasures beyond measure, none would begrudge him; though you were to grant him dominion over ten thousand households, the age would not deem it excessive.

    And yet you, who stand as a model to all ministers and as a pillar of our three-fold realm, who are versed in the ways of heaven, earth, and humanity, who have cultivated the aspirations of the true scholar and possess wisdom, benevolence, and courage together with the talents of a great general—when the western rebellion arose, you shouldered the grave responsibility of supreme command. From the moment you received your orders, you first purged the treacherous conspirators within the court itself. Then, as you led the campaign, you swiftly subdued the northern territories. You fortified the walls, established your encampments, built ramparts across the rivers. You tended your soldiers with care and ease, while frustrating and breaking the enemy's schemes. With a single dawn command, before even exchanging blows, the gathered rebels submitted beneath your banners. You then proclaimed the court's clemency, releasing all the common people from their sufferings.

    From beginning to end, this remarkable strategy flowed from your mastery of both clemency and authority, of both strictness and generosity. To leave such deeds unadorned would be to fail in proper recognition of extraordinary service. Thus have I issued decrees of praise and advanced you to the position of Prime Minister. This is not merely my personal preference, but the will of all the people.

    Now the realm, though barely recovered from chaos, still bears its wounds. Your continued service and counsel are ever more needful if we are to transform this trial into the foundation of national revival. Your steadfast humility cannot serve my greater purpose. Therefore, assume your position without further delay, and trouble me no more with repeated refusals.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'western rebellion' refers to the Khitan invasion, likely the Jurchen incursions of the early 12th century during the Goryeo period.
  - key: ''
    value: Kim Bu-sik (1075-1151) was one of Goryeo's most celebrated statesmen and scholars, known for his military prowess and for compiling the Samguk Sagi (History of the Three Kingdoms).
  - key: ''
    value: The titles listed represent the highest positions in Goryeo's government bureaucracy.
